    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I see two issues with this:\r\n\r\n(1) prohibitive gas costs for increasing/decreasing/getting productivity. Verifying user-supplied proofs of productivity is going to be gas intensive. For example the EIP states:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\n/// Note the best practice will be restrict the callee to prove of productivity's contract address.\r\nfunction increaseProductivity(address user, uint value) external returns (bool);\r\n```\r\nThis proof will be expensive to verify, even more so it if it's standarized in some way (overhead). It also introduces a dependency on either wallets of frontends to generate these proofs. \r\n\r\n\r\n(2) \"Productivity\" is contract-specific, so doesn't lend itself to standardization. \r\n\r\nTypically in DeFi, productivity is not accounted for at the user-level, but rather through the constant updates of global variables (like amount interest accumulated). Users are only given \"shares\" of the pool (typically as an ERC20 token, e.g. cDai on Compound). When a specific user withdraws for example, her \"productivity\" is readily determined by extracting a pro rata share from the interest accrued in addition to the principle. This determination is a simple `div`ision. By keeping track of only (1) initial user share and (2) interest accrued globally (this is updated anytime pokes the contract in any way), the \"productivity\" is determined easily and without any need to increase/decrease productivity at the user level.",
